comment: I'm intrigued by humans' attempt to create a replica of a (biological) thing based primarily on our observations of, and our interactions with, that thing. We are biased to replicate the behaviours and qualities that are pleasing to us, without any deep representation of the sentient experience and existential imperatives that give rise to surface phenomena. I don't believe we can replicate human-like consciousness, for example, without a sense of mortality and a consequent motivation for survival and thriving. If an AGI doesn't know it can die, and isn't enabled with the ability to act to further or diminish its probability of survival, I doubt it will ever really behave in human-like ways.

comment:
Unless A.I. entities are engineered to possess the unassailable feature of self-governance with what we can only anthropomorphically term 'flawless ethics', humankind is doomed: not because it is human and corporeal, but because it will have otherwise surrendered its destiny to something of its own design. Something with as-yet- unrealized but widely anticipated superiority in every field of intellectual endeavor. Surely this will encompass the ageless conflict between 'good' and 'evil'.  

Presuming that these developers are essentially birthing children with the capabilities of independent thought and action, what assurance do we have that these escapees from Pandora's Box -- despite genius efforts in 'teaching' models how to perform -- will 'behave' in a manner that is directed by an unrelenting allegiance to the greater good? Look at our world as it is currently. All true problems are somehow the consequences of human action, reaction and inaction. What 'artificial' flaws in character and judgement might be revealed in A.I., noting its origins? The metaphor that an apple doesn't roll far from the tree that bears it seems appropriate in this context. 

I'm as much an optimist as I am a pessimist. Science is awesome, but it isn't godlike. People shouldn't make the mistake of failing to identify hubris as much as scientific ideals or even genuine altruism as part of the foundation for the Artificial Intelligence movement. I intuitively believe that the paper worlds of dystopia envisioned by the likes of Huxley and Orwell were more prescience than fiction. Would A.I. sense that? Yes, sense, not algorithmically suggest. 

As a layman I certainly oversimplify, but we are making precarious leaps of faith if we overlook the potential of Artificial Intelligence to express the undesirable as well as the glorious in so-called 'orders of magnitude' beyond what we've seen humanly possible. As someone once said, "Unless A.I. entities are engineered to possess the unassailable feature of self-governance with what we can only anthropomorphically term 'flawless ethics', humankind is doomed." ; ] 

The results of 'perfect' A.I. would be too socialistic for my preference. It would be cool to get another 50 turns around the sun. I just hope that neither people nor Artificial Intelligence make the journey miserable.

comment: The ouija (/ˈwiːdʒə/ WEE-jə, /-dʒi/ -⁠jee), also known as a spirit board or talking board, is a flat board marked with the letters of the Latin alphabet, the numbers 0–9, the words "yes", "no", occasionally "hello" and "goodbye", along with various symbols and graphics. It uses a planchette (small heart-shaped piece of wood or plastic) as a movable indicator to spell out messages during a séance. Participants place their fingers on the planchette, and it is moved about the board to spell out words. "Ouija" is a trademark of Hasbro (inherited from Parker Brothers),[1] but is often used generically to refer to any talking board.
